---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-belgium', text: 'Leaving Belgian Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'eu-coordination', text: 'EU Coordination', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-belgium', text: 'Returning to Belgium', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Allianz Care Review', href: '/providers/allianz-care' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Dutch Expat Insurance', href: '/best/dutch-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best French Expat Insurance', href: '/best/french-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'languages', header: 'Languages' },
  { key: 'euNetwork', header: 'EU Network' },
  { key: 'belgiumCoverage', header: 'Belgium Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', languages: 'FR/NL/EN', euNetwork: 'Strong', belgiumCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', languages: 'FR/NL/EN', euNetwork: 'Excellent', belgiumCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€175/mo' },
  { provider: 'DKV Belgium', languages: 'FR/NL/DE', euNetwork: 'Strong', belgiumCoverage: 'Included', price: '€160/mo' },
  { provider: 'AG Insurance', languages: 'FR/NL', euNetwork: 'Good', belgiumCoverage: 'Included', price: '€150/mo' },
  { provider: 'April International', languages: 'FR/EN', euNetwork: 'Strong', belgiumCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€165/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Belgian Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Belgian expats. Find coverage with French and Dutch support for destinations across Europe and worldwide."
  headline="Best Insurance for Belgian Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Belgium's complex but comprehensive healthcare system doesn't travel with you. Here's how to stay covered abroad while protecting your mutualiteit rights."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/belgian-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Belgian expats benefit from the EU's strong coordination rules but need proper coverage regardless of destination. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Belgian expats. Multilingual support (French, Dutch, English), strong global networks.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Excellent for European destinations. Strong networks, good Belgian support, competitive pricing.</li>
    <li><strong>DKV Belgium:</strong> Belgian insurer with international products. Familiar brand, Belgian service standards.</li>
    <li><strong>AG Insurance:</strong> Major Belgian insurer offering international coverage. French and Dutch service.</li>
    <li><strong>April International:</strong> French insurer popular with Francophone Belgians. Strong EU coverage.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Language Support"
    description="Belgium has three official languages. Look for insurers offering support in French, Dutch, or your preferred language. Most international insurers offer excellent English service as well."
    buttonText="Compare Multilingual Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-belgium">Leaving Belgian Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Belgium has a mandatory health insurance system through mutualiteiten (Dutch) / mutualités (French). Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>Mutualiteit Membership</h3>
  <p>
    Your mutualiteit membership (CM, Mutualité Chrétienne, Solidaris, etc.) is linked to Belgian residence and social security contributions. When you leave Belgium, you should inform your mutualiteit and your membership status changes.
  </p>

  <h3>RIZIV/INAMI Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    The Belgian healthcare reimbursement system (RIZIV in Dutch, INAMI in French) only applies to care in Belgium or EU emergencies. Moving abroad ends your regular Belgian healthcare access.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Belgian Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    If you have hospitalisatieverzekering (hospitalization insurance) through work or privately (DKV, AG, Ethias), check whether it can continue abroad. Most Belgian hospital insurance has limited international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>EU Health Insurance Card (EHIC)</h3>
  <p>
    Your Belgian EHIC provides emergency coverage in other EU/EEA countries while you're Belgian-insured. Once you establish residence elsewhere in the EU, you should get that country's EHIC.
  </p>

  <h2 id="eu-coordination">EU Coordination</h2>
  <p>
    Belgium's strong EU ties mean coordination rules apply extensively:
  </p>

  <h3>Working in Another EU Country</h3>
  <p>
    If you work in another EU country, you're generally covered by that country's social security system. Your employer enrolls you locally, and you contribute to the destination country's healthcare.
  </p>

  <h3>Posted Workers (Detachering/Détachement)</h3>
  <p>
    If your Belgian employer posts you temporarily to another EU country (max 24 months typically), you may remain in the Belgian system with an A1 certificate. Check with RSZ/ONSS for posting rules.
  </p>

  <h3>Pension Coordination</h3>
  <p>
    Contributions in other EU countries count toward your Belgian pension. The EU coordinates benefits so you don't lose entitlements by working across borders.
  </p>

  <h3>Non-EU Destinations</h3>
  <p>
    Belgium has limited bilateral agreements outside the EU. For destinations like the US, UK (post-Brexit), or Asia, you need fully independent international coverage.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Cross-Border Workers</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Belgium has many cross-border workers (grensarbeiders/frontaliers) with Netherlands, Germany, France, and Luxembourg. Special rules apply—you may be insured in one country while living in another. Clarify your situation before changing anything.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage with multilingual support suitable for Belgian expats. French, Dutch, and English service is available. Strong networks worldwide make this ideal for any destination.
  </p>

  <p>
    Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited. Belgium coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Belgian expats who want reliable global coverage with multilingual support.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers excellent European coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks throughout the EU make this ideal for Belgian expats staying in Europe. French and Dutch support is available.
  </p>

  <p>
    Good value for comprehensive EU coverage. Belgium coverage can be added.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Belgian expats in EU countries who want strong European networks.
  </p>

  <h3>DKV Belgium</h3>
  <p>
    DKV is one of Belgium's largest health insurers, offering international products for Belgian expats. Familiar service in French, Dutch, and German. Belgium coverage is included automatically.
  </p>

  <p>
    International networks are adequate, strongest in Europe. Good option for those who prefer a familiar Belgian brand.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Belgian expats who want familiar Belgian service and seamless home coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>AG Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    AG Insurance is a major Belgian insurer offering international health products. French and Dutch service, Belgium coverage included. Competitive pricing for Belgian expats.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Belgian expats seeking good value from a familiar Belgian insurer.
  </p>

  <h3>April International</h3>
  <p>
    April International is a French insurer popular among Francophone Belgians. Strong EU coverage, French service, and understanding of Belgian-French cross-border needs.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> French-speaking Belgian expats, especially those in France or French-speaking countries.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Belgian and International Options"
    description="Belgian insurers offer familiar service; international insurers have broader networks. Compare based on your destination and language preferences."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-belgium">Returning to Belgium</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to Belgian healthcare requires rejoining the system:
  </p>

  <h3>Registering Residence</h3>
  <p>
    Register at your gemeentehuis/administration communale within 8 days of arrival. This triggers your integration into Belgian social security.
  </p>

  <h3>Mutualiteit Membership</h3>
  <p>
    Join or rejoin a mutualiteit. You can choose any recognized mutualiteit regardless of which one you had before. Membership is mandatory for residents.
  </p>

  <h3>Contribution Periods</h3>
  <p>
    If returning from another EU country, bring documentation of your social security contributions there. EU coordination ensures these periods count toward your Belgian entitlements.
  </p>

  <h3>Transition Period</h3>
  <p>
    Keep your international insurance active until Belgian coverage is confirmed. Registration and mutualiteit enrollment usually happen quickly, but overlap prevents gaps.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep my mutualiteit abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Membership status changes when you leave Belgian residence. Contact your mutualiteit—some offer affiliated membership for expats, but it doesn't provide full coverage abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Do I need insurance if working in the EU?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">You'll be covered by the destination country's system through employment. Additional private insurance is optional but can improve access.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about my Belgian pension?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">EU coordination protects your pension rights. Contributions in other EU countries count toward your Belgian pension entitlement.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is DKV or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">DKV offers Belgian familiarity and includes Belgium coverage. Cigna has stronger global networks. Choose based on destination and preference.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about UK post-Brexit?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">EU coordination no longer applies to the UK. Belgian expats in the UK need to ensure NHS access through proper visa status or get international insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Which language should I choose for support?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Choose whichever you're most comfortable with in stressful situations. Major insurers offer French, Dutch, and English. Belgian insurers typically offer both French and Dutch.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Belgian expats have excellent options for international coverage. Within the EU, coordination rules may provide base coverage, but private insurance improves access. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for global coverage with multilingual support.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Allianz Care</strong> offers great value for EU destinations. <strong>DKV Belgium</strong> and <strong>AG Insurance</strong> suit those who prefer familiar Belgian service.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before leaving, clarify your situation with your mutualiteit and RSZ/ONSS. Understand whether you'll be covered by the destination country's system or need independent coverage.
  </p>

</PageShell>
